2
00:00:01,034 --> 00:00:02,763
Previously on Desperate Housewives...

3
00:00:02,836 --> 00:00:05,202
If someone hurt her,
I want them dead.

4
00:00:05,305 --> 00:00:06,329
Sometimes...

5
00:00:06,406 --> 00:00:09,170
I'm out of money.
In a few weeks I'll be screwed.

6
00:00:09,242 --> 00:00:11,836
- Think about looking for a job.
- Ha!

7
00:00:11,911 --> 00:00:13,572
The answers...

8
00:00:13,680 --> 00:00:15,841
Tell me what he said
and I can fix it.

9
00:00:15,915 --> 00:00:18,782
- I can't.
...to life's biggest questions...

10
00:00:18,852 --> 00:00:21,013
[Mary Alice on tape]
I had the nightmare.

11
00:00:21,087 --> 00:00:23,248
[Dr. Goldfine] And the name "Angela"?

12
00:00:23,356 --> 00:00:25,916
- [Tape] My real name.
...are buried...

13
00:00:25,992 --> 00:00:28,893
She's not been dead a month
and it's like she never existed.

14
00:00:28,962 --> 00:00:30,520
...under bigger lies.

15
00:00:30,597 --> 00:00:35,762
- Zach was telling Julie about Dana.
- He didn't mean to kill Dana.

16
00:00:40,974 --> 00:00:45,502
Most mothers will tell you
their children are a gift from God.

17
00:00:45,645 --> 00:00:49,604
Most mothers will also tell you
the gifts their children give them

18
00:00:49,682 --> 00:00:52,583
are less than heavenly.

19
00:00:53,586 --> 00:00:58,717
Lynette had suffered through art work
made in kindergarten...

20
00:00:59,692 --> 00:01:03,856
...spice racks made in summer camp...

21
00:01:04,564 --> 00:01:08,591
...and jewelry
made at the scout jambore.

22
00:01:08,701 --> 00:01:10,430
On this day...

23
00:01:10,503 --> 00:01:14,940
...Lynette Scavo received a gift
every mother dreams of.

24
00:01:15,608 --> 00:01:17,974
One she wasn't embarrassed to display.

25
00:01:18,044 --> 00:01:21,172
- Where did you guys get this pot?
- [Twins] We made it.

26
00:01:21,281 --> 00:01:23,841
Really? I love it.

27
00:01:24,651 --> 00:01:29,111
Well, this is the nicest present
you boys have ever given me.

28
00:01:29,222 --> 00:01:33,454
I'll put it out on the front porch
so the whole neighborhood can enjoy it.

29
00:01:34,694 --> 00:01:38,687
Lynette would cherish
the memory of that moment

30
00:01:38,765 --> 00:01:42,030
for the rest of her life.

31
00:01:42,102 --> 00:01:46,334
The memory of that moment
was ruined the very next day.

32
00:01:52,645 --> 00:01:56,103
Mrs. McCluskey,
why are you taking my flower pot?

33
00:01:56,182 --> 00:01:58,582
It's mine. Your boys stole it.

34
00:01:58,651 --> 00:02:02,280
No, no, no. My sons made that
for me for Valentine's Day!

35
00:02:02,388 --> 00:02:06,449
I bought this in Costa Rica
on my last cruise. You see?

36
00:02:06,526 --> 00:02:08,926
It's still got the price tag on it.

37
00:02:10,763 --> 00:02:14,221
What? Nothing more to say?
Cat got your tongue?

38
00:02:14,334 --> 00:02:17,599
You listen to me,
keep your brats off my property.

39
00:02:17,704 --> 00:02:24,075
Yes, most mothers will tell you
their children are a gift from God.

40
00:02:25,178 --> 00:02:28,011
Most mothers will also tell you

41
00:02:28,081 --> 00:02:31,676
there are some days
when you wish you could return them.

42
00:03:13,493 --> 00:03:17,486
It was the day before Valentine's Day
and every man on Wisteria Lane

43
00:03:17,564 --> 00:03:22,001
was preparing for this
most dangerous of holidays.

44
00:03:22,101 --> 00:03:24,467
While some purchased
romantic cards...

45
00:03:27,607 --> 00:03:31,407
...and some brought home
candy and flowers...

46
00:03:31,978 --> 00:03:35,573
and some made dinner reservations
at fancy restaurants...

47
00:03:37,250 --> 00:03:42,654
...others managed to forget
about the day entirely... again.

48
00:03:42,722 --> 00:03:48,661
This flurry of activity was lost
on the women of Wisteria Lane.

49
00:03:48,761 --> 00:03:52,754
They were busy learning
a secret about their neighbors.

50
00:03:52,832 --> 00:03:57,098
A secret
that was positively heartbreaking.

51
00:03:57,170 --> 00:04:00,264
So Paul said
that Zachary killed Dana?

52
00:04:00,340 --> 00:04:01,398
Yeah.

53
00:04:01,474 --> 00:04:05,433
It must have been an accident.
Boys don't just kill their sisters.

54
00:04:05,545 --> 00:04:10,778
That boy is seriously disturbed and
I've forbidden Julie from seeing him.

55
00:04:11,851 --> 00:04:16,447
So this is it. This is the secret
that Mary Alice was trying to protect.

56
00:04:16,522 --> 00:04:18,422
The guilt she lived with.

57
00:04:18,491 --> 00:04:22,120
I never thought I'd say this,
but I kind of feel sorry for Paul.

58
00:04:22,195 --> 00:04:25,528
I wish I could.
I still feel like something's not right.

59
00:04:25,598 --> 00:04:28,624
- What do you mean?
- We've all been in their house.

60
00:04:28,701 --> 00:04:31,397
Have you ever seen a picture
of another kid?

61
00:04:31,537 --> 00:04:34,973
Why keep Dana's baby blanket
and throw out all the photos?

62
00:04:35,041 --> 00:04:36,906
That's a good point.

63
00:04:37,010 --> 00:04:40,707
And why did Mary Alice refer to herself
as "Angela" in therapy?

64
00:04:40,813 --> 00:04:45,216
Mary Alice loved Zach
more than anything in the world.

65
00:04:45,318 --> 00:04:48,014
When you love a child that much...

66
00:04:49,188 --> 00:04:52,180
You're capable of doing
all sorts of things.

67
00:04:55,862 --> 00:04:57,955
Yeah.

68
00:05:03,069 --> 00:05:04,969
[Knocking]

69
00:05:05,805 --> 00:05:11,505
Hello? These were delivered
to my house by mistake. May I?

70
00:05:11,611 --> 00:05:13,511
They're for Mary Alice Young.

71
00:05:14,814 --> 00:05:16,839
Oh, my God.

72
00:05:16,916 --> 00:05:20,511
I, uh... had a standing order
with the florist.

73
00:05:20,620 --> 00:05:22,952
I... forgot to cancel it.

74
00:05:24,557 --> 00:05:28,516
Mary Alice was my wife.
She passed away a few months ago.

75
00:05:31,597 --> 00:05:34,293
I'm very sorry for your loss.

76
00:05:34,367 --> 00:05:35,994
And I'm sorry for yours.

77
00:05:36,069 --> 00:05:39,835
- Pardon?
- Your sister? Martha?

78
00:05:39,972 --> 00:05:43,806
Oh... yes... her.

79
00:05:47,180 --> 00:05:50,115
Good Lord, that's Angela.

80
00:05:51,517 --> 00:05:52,984
What?

81
00:05:53,052 --> 00:05:57,682
Angela Forrest. We worked together
in Utah. It must be 15 years ago.

82
00:05:57,790 --> 00:06:01,954
I'm afraid you're mistaken.
My wife's name was Mary Alice.

83
00:06:02,028 --> 00:06:04,155
She's... never been to Utah.

84
00:06:07,100 --> 00:06:12,663
Well, I could be mistaken.
As I said, it's... been years.

85
00:06:19,679 --> 00:06:22,842
No, Mickey, you're wrong.
I wasn't acting like a diva.

86
00:06:22,949 --> 00:06:27,613
I left the boat show because that
coordinator was making passes at me.

87
00:06:27,687 --> 00:06:30,952
I mean, it's not my fault.
Yao Lin, you missed a spot.

88
00:06:31,023 --> 00:06:35,084
No, spare me the lecture
and just book me another job, quick.

89
00:06:35,161 --> 00:06:39,154
Carlos and I are up to our asses
in bills and we can't pay 'em.

90
00:06:39,232 --> 00:06:41,325
Fine. Bye.

91
00:06:42,969 --> 00:06:46,666
[Speaks Chinese]

92
00:06:49,008 --> 00:06:51,806
- What did you say?
- Nothing.

93
00:06:53,713 --> 00:06:56,580
Are you gonna clean that spot?

94
00:06:56,649 --> 00:06:59,812
- Which one?
- The one I told you to clean.

95
00:07:00,987 --> 00:07:02,818
I get to it.

96
00:07:12,098 --> 00:07:14,623
Clean it now.

97
00:07:14,700 --> 00:07:17,760
- Why?
- Because I said so.

98
00:07:19,172 --> 00:07:23,074
OK. But you got to say please.

99
00:07:24,410 --> 00:07:27,971
[Sighs] Fine. Please.

100
00:07:32,018 --> 00:07:36,853
Anything to get you back on your knees
scrubbing where you belong.

101
00:07:36,923 --> 00:07:40,984
- You're not better than me.
- Excuse me?

102
00:07:41,060 --> 00:07:46,521
The only reason you have anything
in your life is because you're pretty.

103
00:07:46,632 --> 00:07:50,932
One day you'll be old and
when that happens, you'll be nothing.

104
00:07:53,072 --> 00:07:55,768
You are so fired.

105
00:07:56,943 --> 00:07:59,241
No kidding.

106
00:08:03,216 --> 00:08:05,309
[Scoffs]

107
00:08:07,753 --> 00:08:13,419
Ooh, Valentine's Day card. It's pretty.
And meticulously hand-painted.

108
00:08:13,526 --> 00:08:16,518
Whoever sent you that
must really love you.

109
00:08:16,596 --> 00:08:20,259
- And be loaded with talent.
- It's beautiful. Thanks.

110
00:08:22,401 --> 00:08:24,460
We still on for tomorrow night?

111
00:08:24,537 --> 00:08:27,472
I got reservations at Le Petit Fleur.

112
00:08:27,573 --> 00:08:31,339
That place is so pretentious.
I've been dying to go there.

113
00:08:31,410 --> 00:08:34,777
Boys? Get your little fannies inside.

114
00:08:35,948 --> 00:08:37,973
Guys?

115
00:08:38,084 --> 00:08:41,884
Oh, poor, Lynette.
If she doesn't get a new nanny soon,

116
00:08:41,954 --> 00:08:44,787
- she's gonna implode.
- Shh.

117
00:08:48,394 --> 00:08:51,090
Hey, guys.
Who you hiding from?

118
00:08:51,163 --> 00:08:53,791
- Our mom.
- She wants to spank us.

119
00:08:53,866 --> 00:08:56,528
Did you do something bad?

120
00:08:57,136 --> 00:08:59,764
If you hide out too long,
she'll get worried.

121
00:08:59,872 --> 00:09:03,672
Then she'll get madder.
You know what I say? Go on home.

122
00:09:03,776 --> 00:09:07,837
Decent chance you'll have
the rest of day to play.

123
00:09:07,914 --> 00:09:11,680
- [Boys confer quietly]
- Come on, climb aboard.

124
00:09:13,352 --> 00:09:15,445
All right.

125
00:09:16,622 --> 00:09:19,853
- Pretty impressive.
- Oh, I love kids.

126
00:09:19,926 --> 00:09:22,019
Can't wait to have my own some day.

127
00:09:22,128 --> 00:09:23,152
Oh!

128
00:09:34,974 --> 00:09:38,569
- We don't want to get spanked.
- We promise we'll be good.

129
00:09:38,678 --> 00:09:41,875
Too late. You stole.
And then you lied.

130
00:09:41,948 --> 00:09:45,440
Even worse, you made me look bad
in front of Mrs. McCluskey,

131
00:09:45,518 --> 00:09:48,180
who you know
is Mommy's sworn enemy.

132
00:09:48,254 --> 00:09:50,882
Time to pick your poison.

133
00:09:50,957 --> 00:09:54,859
How about a belt? It's a classic.

134
00:09:54,927 --> 00:09:58,488
Well, we could go
with the old hickory stick.

135
00:09:58,598 --> 00:09:59,895
It's a cliché,

136
00:09:59,999 --> 00:10:01,523
but it's effective.

137
00:10:01,634 --> 00:10:06,094
I know. We'll go with the spatula.
The holes give it less wind resistance.

138
00:10:07,139 --> 00:10:10,074
- Moves faster.
- [All] No! No, no, no, no.

139
00:10:10,176 --> 00:10:14,636
Guys! Hey, my hands are tied.
Thieves get spanked.

140
00:10:14,714 --> 00:10:16,773
Just the way it works.

141
00:10:18,584 --> 00:10:20,745
- Unless...
- Unless what?

142
00:10:22,421 --> 00:10:25,948
For a first time offence,
if you swear,

143
00:10:26,092 --> 00:10:30,426
cross your heart,
that you will never, never steal again,

144
00:10:30,529 --> 00:10:34,124
and you write Mrs. McCluskey
a letter of apology,

145
00:10:34,233 --> 00:10:36,098
I will let it slide.

146
00:10:36,202 --> 00:10:38,102
- [All] OK!
- Yeah! We swear.

147
00:10:38,170 --> 00:10:43,540
All right, start with
"Dear Mrs. McCluskey..."

148
00:10:45,578 --> 00:10:48,411
Mommy? Why are you smiling?

149
00:10:48,481 --> 00:10:51,746
Do you know what
"psychological warfare" means?

150
00:10:51,817 --> 00:10:54,980
- No.
- Well, too bad for you.

151
00:10:55,087 --> 00:10:57,578
OK, start with a big "M", "C"...

152
00:10:58,624 --> 00:10:59,682
Good.

153
00:11:00,559 --> 00:11:04,188
Rex and I are hosting a dinner party
for ten next week.

154
00:11:04,296 --> 00:11:07,697
We're using our best china
and serving duck.

155
00:11:07,767 --> 00:11:10,600
So, you and Rex
are a couple again?

156
00:11:10,670 --> 00:11:15,903
Yes. You know, that's one of things
I hated most about our separation.

157
00:11:15,975 --> 00:11:18,375
Not being able
to throw dinner parties.

158
00:11:18,444 --> 00:11:23,177
There's just something so civilized
and elegant about them, don't you think?

159
00:11:23,249 --> 00:11:27,379
I take it you've resolved
your feelings about his infidelity?

160
00:11:27,453 --> 00:11:30,945
Let's just say
I've put them in an imaginary box

161
00:11:31,023 --> 00:11:34,459
and don't plan on looking
at them for a while.

162
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:38,189
Is that the healthiest way
to achieve a reconciliation?

163
00:11:38,297 --> 00:11:40,390
Well, it won't be easy at first.

164
00:11:40,466 --> 00:11:44,960
There'll be a lot of forced smiles
and perfunctory love-making,

165
00:11:45,037 --> 00:11:49,201
but after a few decades whiz by,
I'm sure I'll find a way to forgive him.

166
00:11:49,275 --> 00:11:51,334
Well, as long as you have a plan.

167
00:11:56,582 --> 00:11:58,812
I do want to forgive him,

168
00:11:58,884 --> 00:12:03,821
but... there's something
he's still not telling me.

169
00:12:05,357 --> 00:12:07,450
Really?

170
00:12:08,661 --> 00:12:11,926
I think it has something
to do with why he had the affair.

171
00:12:12,064 --> 00:12:14,191
- Have you confronted him?
- Once.

172
00:12:14,266 --> 00:12:16,928
You should have seen
the look in his eyes.

173
00:12:17,002 --> 00:12:21,098
He was terrified I'd figure it out.

174
00:12:23,042 --> 00:12:26,034
You know what it is, don't you?

175
00:12:26,145 --> 00:12:28,409
Bree, I can't discuss other patients.

176
00:12:29,982 --> 00:12:32,041
I realize that.

177
00:12:35,321 --> 00:12:39,121
This thing that he's hiding...
Is it bad?

178
00:12:43,129 --> 00:12:46,895
Oh, OK, um... uh...

179
00:12:46,966 --> 00:12:49,457
Maybe it's better that I don't know.

180
00:12:49,602 --> 00:12:52,867
Bree, how does this reconciliation
have a chance

181
00:12:52,972 --> 00:12:57,341
if the two of you can't be honest
about the innermost parts of your life?

182
00:12:57,409 --> 00:12:59,673
We're, um... W.A.S.P. S, Dr. Goldfine.

183
00:12:59,779 --> 00:13:03,545
Not acknowledging the elephant
in the room is what we do best.

184
00:13:03,582 --> 00:13:08,315
You'd settle for that? A life
filled with repression and denial?

185
00:13:09,655 --> 00:13:14,615
And the dinner parties.
Don't forget the dinner parties.

186
00:13:20,933 --> 00:13:24,494
And, uh, over there
you got your queens and, uh...

187
00:13:24,637 --> 00:13:27,868
Your Quad Spring series,
and your deluxe 1000s,

188
00:13:27,940 --> 00:13:33,435
all the way to the Imperial Paradise.
[Laughs] Sweet racket, huh?

189
00:13:33,546 --> 00:13:38,677
Sometimes I wake up in the morning
and I can't believe I'm the Siesta King.

190
00:13:38,751 --> 00:13:40,878
Except for how I am.

191
00:13:40,986 --> 00:13:43,011
Very impressive.

192
00:13:43,122 --> 00:13:47,354
So, where does the photographer
want me for the shoot?

193
00:13:47,493 --> 00:13:50,985
Uh, didn't your agent tell you?
There's no shoot.

194
00:13:51,096 --> 00:13:54,623
Well, then what did you hire me for?

195
00:13:56,035 --> 00:14:00,301
[Siesta King] You've heard
the expression "sex sells"? That's you.

196
00:14:00,372 --> 00:14:04,069
You're to remind people
there's a lot of fun things they can do

197
00:14:04,143 --> 00:14:08,603
on a Siesta King mattress
that don't involve slep. Get it?

198
00:14:30,402 --> 00:14:34,771
It is often said that good fences
make good neighbors.

199
00:14:36,242 --> 00:14:38,710
But as Lynette was about to discover,

200
00:14:38,811 --> 00:14:42,338
the fence might just ned
a little barbed wire

201
00:14:42,448 --> 00:14:44,712
if the neighbor is Mrs. McCluskey.

202
00:14:44,817 --> 00:14:46,717
Hey!

203
00:14:50,089 --> 00:14:53,718
What do you think you are doing?
Get out of here.

204
00:14:53,826 --> 00:14:57,728
Your little criminals snuck into
my house and stole my wall clock.

205
00:14:57,830 --> 00:14:58,854
What?

206
00:14:58,931 --> 00:15:02,924
It was a hand-painted, purple
and white wall clock. My son made it.

207
00:15:03,035 --> 00:15:04,969
You sure you didn't misplace it?

208
00:15:05,037 --> 00:15:08,529
No offence, but you probably
forget where you put things.

209
00:15:08,607 --> 00:15:11,599
No offence,
but you should be sterilized.

210
00:15:11,677 --> 00:15:14,271
My boys do not
break into people's houses.

211
00:15:14,380 --> 00:15:16,644
They may have stolen your flowerpot.

212
00:15:16,715 --> 00:15:20,116
- They apologized for that.
- They wrote a note.

213
00:15:20,219 --> 00:15:23,814
The coward's way out.
They should've apologized in person.

214
00:15:23,889 --> 00:15:27,586
- This has been fun. But now...
- You let those boys run wild.

215
00:15:27,693 --> 00:15:31,891
Toys all over the yard, bikes out
in the street. It's a disgrace.

216
00:15:31,997 --> 00:15:33,021
Get out!

217
00:15:33,098 --> 00:15:36,261
Those boys would've been
better off raised by wolves.

218
00:15:36,368 --> 00:15:39,633
God knows they would have been cleaner.

219
00:15:44,343 --> 00:15:46,903
Valentine's Day is tomorrow.

220
00:15:46,979 --> 00:15:50,437
I know. I already bought your gifts.

221
00:15:50,549 --> 00:15:53,074
Roses and English toffee?

222
00:15:53,185 --> 00:15:56,643
Mm-hm. Just like always.

223
00:15:56,755 --> 00:16:00,054
Yes. And I suppose we'll make love
tomorrow night, too.

224
00:16:01,160 --> 00:16:03,720
That is our little tradition.

225
00:16:03,796 --> 00:16:06,697
Good. I'm looking forward to it.

226
00:16:14,373 --> 00:16:17,206
Are you looking forward to it?

227
00:16:18,243 --> 00:16:19,267
What?

228
00:16:19,378 --> 00:16:22,404
I know that I don't...
please you sexually,

229
00:16:22,481 --> 00:16:26,110
so I was wondering if you were
looking forward to being with me.

230
00:16:26,185 --> 00:16:27,584
Oh, for God's sake.

231
00:16:27,653 --> 00:16:32,113
I'm sorry. I thought I could pretend
that this doesn't upset me anymore.

232
00:16:32,224 --> 00:16:34,749
- But I can't.
- Please, don't do this.

233
00:16:34,827 --> 00:16:39,526
You went to another woman for sex
to give you something I couldn't.

234
00:16:39,598 --> 00:16:42,328
At least tell me
what that something is.

235
00:16:42,401 --> 00:16:45,495
- Bree, I can't.
- Why not?

236
00:16:47,740 --> 00:16:49,605
[Sighs]

237
00:16:50,476 --> 00:16:55,778
Rex, please tell me. Let me
