478
00:36:34,559 --> 00:36:36,618
You know that, right?

479
00:36:37,762 --> 00:36:39,389
Yeah.

480
00:36:43,801 --> 00:36:48,363
I'm gonna go outside
and let you rest for a while.

481
00:36:52,977 --> 00:36:57,710
Thanks...
for being so understanding.

482
00:37:09,427 --> 00:37:11,520
[Policeman] Ma'am.

483
00:37:13,331 --> 00:37:17,927
Mr. Delfino? I'm Officer Russell,
this is Officer Walters.

484
00:37:18,002 --> 00:37:20,300
Uh, we'd like to
ask you a few questions.

485
00:37:41,759 --> 00:37:44,387
What do you want?

486
00:37:44,462 --> 00:37:47,625
The boys have something
they'd like to say to you.

487
00:37:53,070 --> 00:37:58,064
I have some tea heating on the stove.
Perhaps you'd better come inside, boys.

488
00:38:03,581 --> 00:38:06,812
What about you, Lynette?
Do you have anything to say?

489
00:38:08,386 --> 00:38:11,719
No. I'll just wait out here.

490
00:38:11,789 --> 00:38:13,848
Suit yourself.

491
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:26,163
You boys want some peanut brittle?

492
00:38:26,237 --> 00:38:27,864
Go ahead.

493
00:38:27,938 --> 00:38:31,066
Don't get any crumbs on my floor.
Move over.

494
00:38:34,812 --> 00:38:38,270
OK, go ahead.
Make with the apology.

495
00:38:40,251 --> 00:38:42,116
We're sorry.

496
00:38:43,154 --> 00:38:47,784
That's it, huh?
Didn't you know stealing is wrong?

497
00:38:48,626 --> 00:38:51,322
- How old are you anyway?
- We're six.

498
00:38:51,429 --> 00:38:53,920
- And how old are you?
- Five.

499
00:38:54,965 --> 00:38:57,866
Boy, your mother
just pops them out, doesn't she?

500
00:38:57,968 --> 00:39:00,562
How old are you?

501
00:39:00,638 --> 00:39:03,937
- How old do you think?
- 150.

502
00:39:05,309 --> 00:39:08,176
Hurry up and eat your peanut brittle.

503
00:39:13,217 --> 00:39:15,310
Who's that?

504
00:39:18,422 --> 00:39:20,481
That's my little boy.

505
00:39:20,558 --> 00:39:22,856
Where does he live?

506
00:39:24,161 --> 00:39:27,392
- He died when he was 12.
- How come?

507
00:39:28,265 --> 00:39:32,998
He got sick.
He was a little terror like you three.

508
00:39:35,906 --> 00:39:37,999
You would've liked him.

509
00:39:40,010 --> 00:39:42,911
Now, you done with the peanut brittle?

510
00:39:42,980 --> 00:39:44,777
Let's go.

511
00:39:48,252 --> 00:39:51,346
Now, I wanna say something
to you before you go.

512
00:39:51,422 --> 00:39:53,913
What you did was wrong,

513
00:39:54,024 --> 00:39:58,961
but it's nice you got a present
for your Mom for Valentine's Day.

514
00:40:00,598 --> 00:40:03,328
Nobody's ever gonna love you
like your mother.

515
00:40:04,969 --> 00:40:07,028
All right, let's go.

516
00:40:09,907 --> 00:40:11,534
Get the hell out of my house.

517
00:40:11,642 --> 00:40:16,670
In her heart, Lynette knew she would
probably never love her neighbor,

518
00:40:16,747 --> 00:40:23,050
never realizing love was the one thing
she and her neighbor had in common.

519
00:40:36,233 --> 00:40:38,064
- Hi.
- Hey, Lynette.

520
00:40:41,539 --> 00:40:44,007
- Um...
- What's wrong?

521
00:40:44,074 --> 00:40:49,068
My kids have been on a thieving jag.
Stealing stuff from the neighborhood.

522
00:40:49,146 --> 00:40:50,477
I'm so sorry.

523
00:40:50,548 --> 00:40:54,109
I know. They're being punished.
Probably for life.

524
00:40:54,218 --> 00:40:57,710
But... I needed you to see something.

525
00:40:59,290 --> 00:41:02,851
They stole it from Mike's garage.
From inside his workbench.

526
00:41:02,927 --> 00:41:04,224
Your Mike.

527
00:41:09,800 --> 00:41:13,736
- So?
- Read the engraving.

528
00:41:17,875 --> 00:41:19,638
[Susan gasps]

529
00:41:21,545 --> 00:41:25,003
- Is that blood?
- I don't know.

530
00:41:25,115 --> 00:41:28,482
What... what does this mean?

531
00:41:29,720 --> 00:41:30,846
I don't know.

532
00:41:41,265 --> 00:41:45,759
It's impossible to grasp
just how powerful love is.

533
00:41:46,737 --> 00:41:49,797
It can sustain us
through trying times...

534
00:41:54,144 --> 00:41:58,513
...or motivate us
to make extraordinary sacrifices.

535
00:42:01,151 --> 00:42:06,316
It can force decent men
to commit the darkest deds.

536
00:42:07,658 --> 00:42:14,063
Or compel ordinary women
to search for hidden truths.

537
00:42:16,166 --> 00:42:18,657
And long after we're gone,

538
00:42:18,736 --> 00:42:22,604
love remains,
burned into our memories.

539
00:42:25,943 --> 00:42:28,844
We all search for love.

540
00:42:28,913 --> 00:42:30,642
But some of us,

541
00:42:30,781 --> 00:42:34,376
after we've found it,

542
00:42:34,451 --> 00:42:36,544
wish we hadn't.

